My first forecast wasn't officially submitted at the time I made it, but I had predicted with 70% certainty that the price would be between 140 and 160, as I was confident based on the trends of the price over the past 6 months that it would stay relatively stagnant in the month of February, however there were still several weeks left in the month where a large fluctuation, perhaps a natural disaster or economic unrest globally, that could have caused the price to rise or fall dramatically.
I think I am now the most confident I have been from the three predictions thus far, as there have not been any major fluctuations in the potential causes I have analyzed over the past few weeks.
It was 147.4 points on average in January 2023, up 0.1 percent from December.

I am 95% confident that the FAO cereals price index for February 2023 will be more than 140.0 but less than 160.0. Throughout all of the forecasts that I have made, I have thought that this is what the cereals price index would be. After running a regression and analyzing specific data sets, I am more confident in selecting this interval for the price index. This is because my regression showed that there was a positive relation between the amount of cereals produced and the cereal price index. So this means that as the amount of cereals produced increases that the Cereals Price Index also increases. According to the US Department of Agriculture, "this month, there are no changes to the 2022/23 domestic supply of corn, sorghum or oats - while barley imports are up slightly from January." (USDA, Feb 10. 23). According to the research that I have conducted, the production of cereals is not varying much from January so I think it is safe to assume that the FAO cereals price index will be relatively the same for February. This is why I think that the FAO cereals price index will be between 140 and 160.

The FAO Cereals Price Index has remained relatively stable between 145-152 over the past 7 months or so, and without any major influences on the global economy or food supply over the past 2 weeks, I don't think a drastic change in the index is incoming for February. There were not extreme weather patterns in areas crucial for the grain/cereals economy, and major countries such as the United States did not see economic recessions. Therefore, I am predicting with 82% confidence that the FAO Cereals Price Index will be between 140 and 160 in the month of February. In the chance that an extreme change does happen to the price index, I predict with 15% certainty that it will be between 120 and 140, and 3% certainty that it will be between 160 and 180.

My prediction is that the FAO cereals price index for February 2023 will be above 140.0 and less than 160.0. This is because in January the price index was 147.4. In all of the sources that I have found, I have seen that the global prices for cereals is staying relatively the same. For example, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations published an article titled, Global Food Prices Decline Further in January. According to this article, various segments of the FAO food price index are decreasing (such as vegetable oils, dairy and sugar) but that the price for cereal is neither decreasing or increasing. This is a statement that I have found is supported by various sources. It is because of this that I think the FAO cereal price index for February would be similar to what it was in January. Resulting from this, I am 89% confident that the FAO Cereals Price Index for February 2022 will be between 140.0 and 160.0.

I am 87% confident that the value of the FAO cereals price index for February 2023 will be be less than 160 but more than 140. This is because the FAO cereals price index for January was 147.4. The average value for the year 2022 was 154.7. From December 2022 to January 2023, there was a slight increase in the FAO cereals price index. From looking at how the value fluctuated in 2022, there is a pattern of their being an increase followed by a decrease. Due to this, I think that the price value for February will be an increase from January, making the value between 140 and 160.
Jan value = 147.4. It would require an extreme drop or an even more extreme increase for the result to end up outside bin 3.

The Nov index value was released early, 5 days ago: 150.4. The index has been between 145 and 151 for the past 5 months. I think it would probably take a large shock for the result to end up outside bin 3 at this point, although the index can be volatile.

Very roughly, wheat prices fell ~7% in Oct, but rice prices jumped ~9%. So, I'd guess that the cereals index for Nov will end up slightly higher than the Oct value, perhaps around 154-156. Much lower prices (<140) are looking a little less likely for Feb, but the possibility of >160 doesn't look small to me, given that the index was at 152.3 for Oct and there are 4 months of data left in the forecast.

The index has been falling since May, with a big fall in July in particular. Economic and military uncertainties remain.
The index continues to fall gently. Barring some new shock, I expect the trend to be generally downward into 2023.

I can picture prices moving in either direction: up from more crop destruction/export prevention in Ukraine, bad weather, high fertilizer prices, etc.; or down from things settling down and the market adjusting to current prices. I'm not sure why the crowd is so low on the 140-160 bin, as the current index value is just over that.

While I have been consistently bullish on food prices for this year, I am inclined to tilt slightly towards either the status quo or singificant disruption rather than small continued increases into historic territories compared to the crowd, for the following reasons:

@belikewater - good analysis, and thanks for looping me in on this question. This is a natural progression of the fertilizer price index forecast! I agree with you that the market has not reacted particularly strongly to the Ukrainian conflict. However, in terms of an outlook to Feb 2023 I have a different take (I think prices will rise and may surpass the peak of 169.5 seen in April). I'm pessimistic on the mid-term effects of the cereal’s shortage issue stemming from the Ukrainian crisis and poor harvests globally. I think we will witness a whiplash effect upon the supply chain that begins to hit early 2023. I need to do more thinking about how all of this information fits together, and the probabilities, but this is my initial thinking and forecast.

The market sure seems to think prices will remain high in Feb, so I'm adjusting my forecast upward. I worry about Ukraine's harvest being substantially lower than expected for any number of reasons, Ukraine not being able to export as much as expected, fertilizer costs, fuel costs, and the generally upward pandemic trend. My gut feeling is that the question will end up in bin 3, but I'm giving equal weight to bin 4 just in case things get out of control, and some weight on bin 5 just in case, as well. I think it would take even greater shocks than we have been seeing to push prices into bin 4 or higher, but maybe I'm wrong, and maybe such a shock might happen. Flocks of black swans lately.

The futures markets sure don't picture grain prices coming down in the time frame of this forecast - but then again, they largely mirror today's prices with opinions about the long-term superimposed on top, and they fluctuate with daily prices. In any case, I'm eliminating bin 1 here based on today's USDA reports - but also eliminating the last bin and lowering my forecasts on the other high bins based on how little the market reacted to the reports, in the grand scheme of things. Also noting that the index fell 0.6 points to 169.5 in April. I think bins 3 and 4 are most likely.
Some analysts are predicting another 40% increase in wheat and similar in other cereals.

I believe the value of the FAO Cereals Price Index for February 2023 will be more than 180.0. It was predicted to rise 1.5% in 2022 and there has been a 3% increase in February. Currently, it is 159.3 and is expected to follow the pattern of it rising.
Due to food shortages, the pandemic, and the war with Russia and Ukraine is if affecting our food prices.

One thing that disturbs me about Ukraine forecasts (e.g., that 70% of the spring crops will get planted, etc.) is that I read today that a survey of Ukrainian farmers found that they had 20% of the fuel they needed for planting. If they only end up with 20% of the fuel they need, or 30% or even 50%, how are they going to plant 70% of their normal levels of crops overall? Adjusting my forecast a little higher.

This is a great and important question. The cereals index has trended upward since the pandemic started, and the war on Ukraine has bumped it up even higher. And the prospects for agricultural output and exports in the short and medium term in Ukraine don't look good, and exports from Russia are also curtailed. Wheat futures markets anticipate prices staying about at current levels until next summer, but wheat futures on those time scales tend to track whatever current prices are. So I take the futures prices with a grain of salt.
